, # tabPanel("Why use ANCOVA?", # includeHTML("whyuseANCOVA.html") # tags$iframe(src = 'AncovaR-test/whyuseANCOVA.html') # ) ) server = function(session, input, output) { ############################################ # _____ _ _ # # / ___| | | | # # \ `--.| |__ __ _ _ __ ___ __| | # # `--. \ '_ \ / _` | '__/ _ \/ _` | # # /\__/ / | | | (_| | | | __/ (_| | # # \____/|_| |_|\__,_|_| \___|\__,_| # # # ############################################ ############ I have no idea why I have to make two of them. ################## ############ If I try to reuse, only one panel will work. ################## output$ANCOVA_guide_title1 <- renderUI({ HTML("

Understanding Your ANCOVA Model Through Plots

") }) output$ANCOVA_guide_title2 <- renderUI({ HTML("

Understanding Your ANCOVA Model Through Plots

") }) guide_visible <- reactiveVal(FALSE) # Observe the button click to toggle visibility observeEvent(input$toggle_button, { guide_visible(!guide_visible()) }) # Render UI conditionally output$conditional_guide1 <- renderUI({ if (guide_visible()) { bigtext <- "

1. Histogram of Residuals

This plot helps assess the normality of residuals. Look for a bell-shaped distribution of the residuals. If the histogram shows substantial skewness or kurtosis, it might indicate that the normality assumption is violated, which can affect the validity of your ANCOVA results.


How to interpret: If the residuals form a roughly symmetrical, bell-shaped curve, the normality assumption is likely satisfied. If the distribution shows significant skewness or outliers, you may need to consider data transformation or other remedial measures.

2. Normal Q-Q Plot

This plot compares the quantiles of the residuals with the quantiles of a normal distribution. Points lying on or near the reference line suggest that the residuals follow a normal distribution.


How to interpret: Examine where the points deviate from the diagonal line. Deviations from the line at either or both ends suggest departures from normality, typically indicating heavy tails or skewness.

3. Residuals vs. Fitted Plot

This plot allows you to check the assumption of homoscedasticity (equal variance across levels of the independent variable). The residuals should be randomly scattered around the horizontal line (residuals = 0).


How to interpret: Look for a random pattern without visible trends or structures. Patterns such as funnels (increasing or decreasing spread) or curves may indicate heteroscedasticity or model misfit.

4. Scale-Location Plot

This plot, which shows the square root of the standardized residuals versus fitted values, is another test for homoscedasticity. Ideally, you want the points to form a horizontal band.


How to interpret: Look for a horizontal line with equally spread points. Patterns, such as fanning or non-linear shapes, suggest non-constant variance, indicating potential issues with homoscedasticity.

" HTML(bigtext) } }) output$conditional_guide2 <- renderUI({ if (guide_visible()) { bigtext <- "

1. Histogram of Residuals

This plot helps assess the normality of residuals. Look for a bell-shaped distribution of the residuals. If the histogram shows substantial skewness or kurtosis, it might indicate that the normality assumption is violated, which can affect the validity of your ANCOVA results.


How to interpret: If the residuals form a roughly symmetrical, bell-shaped curve, the normality assumption is likely satisfied. If the distribution shows significant skewness or outliers, you may need to consider data transformation or other remedial measures.

2. Normal Q-Q Plot

This plot compares the quantiles of the residuals with the quantiles of a normal distribution. Points lying on or near the reference line suggest that the residuals follow a normal distribution.


How to interpret: Examine where the points deviate from the diagonal line. Deviations from the line at either or both ends suggest departures from normality, typically indicating heavy tails or skewness.

3. Residuals vs. Fitted Plot

This plot allows you to check the assumption of homoscedasticity (equal variance across levels of the independent variable). The residuals should be randomly scattered around the horizontal line (residuals = 0).


How to interpret: Look for a random pattern without visible trends or structures. Patterns such as funnels (increasing or decreasing spread) or curves may indicate heteroscedasticity or model misfit.

4. Scale-Location Plot

This plot, which shows the square root of the standardized residuals versus fitted values, is another test for homoscedasticity. Ideally, you want the points to form a horizontal band.


How to interpret: Look for a horizontal line with equally spread points. Patterns, such as fanning or non-linear shapes, suggest non-constant variance, indicating potential issues with homoscedasticity.

" HTML(bigtext) } }) mod_check = function(model, color_col) { residuals = model$residuals linewidth = 1 hist = ggplot(model, aes(x = residuals)) + geom_histogram(aes(y = after_stat(density)), bins = 30) + geom_density(linewidth = linewidth, aes(color = 'Distribution of\nResiduals')) + ggtitle('Normality of Residuals') + stat_function( fun = dnorm, aes(color = 'Normal\nDistribution'), args = list(mean = mean(residuals), sd = sd(residuals)), linewidth = linewidth ) + scale_color_manual('Distributions', values = c('#3333FF', '#FF3333')) + xlab('Residuals') + ylab('Density') + custom_gg + theme(legend.position = 'top') checks = autoplot(model, which = 1:3, colour = color_col) + custom_gg qq_plot = checks[[2]] resid_v_fit = checks[[1]] scale_loc = checks[[3]] # There must be a better way to do this qq_plot[[2]][[2]]$aes_params$colour = 'white' qq_plot[[2]][[2]]$aes_params$size = 0.5 qq_plot[[2]][[3]]$aes_params$colour = 'white' resid_v_fit[[2]][[2]]$aes_params$colour = 'white' resid_v_fit[[2]][[3]]$aes_params$colour = 'white' resid_v_fit[[2]][[3]]$aes_params$size = 0.5 resid_v_fit[[2]][[4]]$aes_params$colour = 'white' scale_loc[[2]][[2]]$aes_params$colour = 'white' scale_loc[[2]][[3]]$aes_params$colour = 'white' if ('cat_factor' %in% names(model$model)) { qq_plot = qq_plot + labs(color = 'Group', fill = 'Group') resid_v_fit = resid_v_fit + labs(color = 'Group', fill = 'Group') scale_loc = scale_loc + labs(color = 'Group', fill = 'Group') } checks = hist + (qq_plot / (resid_v_fit + scale_loc) + plot_layout(guides = 'collect', nrow = 2)) + plot_annotation(theme = custom_gg) + plot_layout(ncol = 2) return(checks) } output$data_expectation = renderUI({ description = "

Data Input Format

AncovaR expects the input data to be in wide format. In wide format, each row represents an individual, and each column represents a measurement about that individual. Here is an example to illustrate the structure:


%s " tbl = data.frame( Genotype = c("WT", "WT", "WT", "WT", "KO", "KO", "KO", "KO"), Drug = c( "Vehicle", "Drug", "Vehicle", "Drug", "Vehicle", "Drug", "Vehicle", "Drug" ), EnergyExpenditure = c(10.1, 10.17, 10.2, 9.36, 6.31, 4.82, 5.66, 7.35), Mass = c(35, 37, 28, 31, 22, 25, 21, 24) ) tbl = tbl %>% kbl() %>% kable_styling("striped", full_width = F) %>% as.character() HTML(sprintf(description, tbl)) }) output$features_list <- renderUI({ HTML( "

Planned Features:

  • Examples of bad plots for the model fit check plots
  • Support for Excel files
  • UI that is reactive to page width
  • Downloadable plots and statistical outputs
" ) }) ########################################################### # _____ ______ _ # # | _ | | ___| | | # # | | | |_ __ ___ ______| |_ __ _ ___| |_ ___ _ __ # # | | | | '_ \ / _ \______| _/ _` |/ __| __/ _ \| '__| # # \ \_/ / | | | __/ | || (_| | (__| || (_) | | # # \___/|_| |_|\___| \_| \__,_|\___|\__\___/|_| # # # ########################################################### # Data handling for one factor analysis data1 = reactive({ validate(need(input$file1, 'Please upload a CSV file')) inFile = input$file1 if (is.null(inFile)) return(NULL) df = read.csv(inFile$datapath, na.strings = c('', 'NA', '#N/A')) return(df) }) data2 = reactive({ df3 = data1() updateSelectInput(session, 'yval', choices = colnames(df3)) updateSelectInput(session, 'factor', choices = colnames(df3)) updateSelectInput(session, 'covariate', choices = colnames(df3)) return(df3) }) output$normal1 = renderUI({ df = data2() validate( need(!is.na(df[[input$yval]]), "Please select a Y variable."), need(is.numeric(df[[input$yval]]), 'Y variable must be numeric.'), need(!is.factor(df[[input$yval]]), 'Y Variable cannot be a factor.') ) and_dar = ad.test(df[[input$yval]])[['p.value']] shapiro = shapiro.test(df[[input$yval]])[['p.value']] pcutoff = 0.05 ynorm = if (and_dar > pcutoff && shapiro > pcutoff) { 'Your y variable is normally distributed according to both Shapiro-Wilk and Anderson-Darling tests. Proceed with ANCOVA.' } else if (and_dar > pcutoff && shapiro < pcutoff) { '

Your y variable is normally distributed according to the Anderson-Darling test but not the Shapiro-Wilk test. Caution is advised.

' } else if (and_dar < pcutoff && shapiro > pcutoff) { '

Your y variable is normally distributed according to the Shapiro-Wilk test but not the Anderson-Darling test. Caution is advised.

' } else { '

Your y variable is not normally distributed. Serious caution advised.

' } HTML(ynorm) }) # Plot one-way plots output$raw_plot1 = renderPlot({ df = data2() scatterplot = ggplot( data = df, aes_string( x = input$covariate, y = input$yval, color = input$factor, shape = input$factor ) ) + geom_point() + stat_smooth(method = 'lm') + custom_gg + theme(legend.position = 'right') + labs( title = 'Covariate vs. Y Variable', fill = 'Group', color = 'Group', shape = 'Group' ) groupedplot = ggplot(data = df, aes_string( x = input$factor, y = input$yval, fill = input$factor )) + geom_boxplot(color = 'black') + geom_point(position = position_jitterdodge(jitter.width = 0.2, dodge.width = 0.75)) + custom_gg + theme(legend.position = 'right') + labs(title = 'Group vs. Y Variable', fill = 'Group', color = 'Group') y_dens = ggplot(data = df, aes_string( x = input$yval, fill = input$factor, color = input$factor )) + geom_density(alpha = 0.5, linewidth = 1, colour = 'black') + geom_rug(linewidth = 1, length = unit(0.08, 'npc')) + custom_gg + labs( title = 'Y Variable Distribution', y = 'Density', fill = 'Group', color = 'Group' ) + scale_y_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0.1, 0))) + theme(legend.position = 'right') cov_dens = ggplot(data = df, aes_string( x = input$covariate, fill = input$factor, color = input$factor )) + geom_density(alpha = 0.5, linewidth = 1, colour = 'black') + geom_rug(linewidth = 1, length = unit(0.08, 'npc')) + custom_gg + labs( title = 'Covariate Distribution', y = 'Density', fill = 'Group', color = 'Group' ) + scale_y_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0.1, 0))) + theme(legend.position = 'right') combined = (scatterplot | groupedplot) / (y_dens | cov_dens) + plot_annotation(theme = custom_gg) combined + plot_annotation( title = 'Raw Data Visualization', theme = list( plot.title = element_text(size = 20), panel.border = element_blank() ) ) + plot_layout(guides = 'collect') }) output$modelchecks1_int = renderPlot({ model = ancova_model1() model = model[['anc_int']] if (is.null(model)) { return("No model available - please ensure data is uploaded and valid selections are made.") } checks = mod_check(model = model, color = input$factor) checks }) output$modelchecks1_no_int = renderPlot({ model = ancova_model1() model = model[['anc_no_int']] if (is.null(model)) { return("No model available - please ensure data is uploaded and valid selections are made.") } checks = mod_check(model = model, color = input$factor) checks }) # ANCOVA Explanation for One Factor Analysis output$ancovaExplanation = renderUI({ model = ancova_model1() if (is.null(model)) { return("No model available - please ensure data is uploaded and valid selections are made.") } # Extract ANCOVA summaries ancova_with_int = Anova(model[['anc_int']], type = 'III') ancova_without_int = Anova(model[['anc_no_int']], type = 'III') # Determine rows for coloring based on p-values pval = input$pval color.green_with <- which(ancova_with_int[, "Pr(>F)"] < pval) color.red_with <- which(ancova_with_int[, "Pr(>F)"] >= pval) color.green_without <- which(ancova_without_int[, "Pr(>F)"] < pval) color.red_without <- which(ancova_without_int[, "Pr(>F)"] >= pval) # Create HTML tables with `kable` ancova_summary_with_int <- ancova_with_int %>% kbl() %>% kable_styling("striped", full_width = F) %>% row_spec(color.green_with, color = "white", background = "#00AA00") %>% row_spec(color.red_with, color = "white", background = "#AA0000") %>% as.character() # Convert it to character to embed HTML within UI ancova_summary_without_int <- ancova_without_int %>% kbl() %>% kable_styling("striped", full_width = F) %>% row_spec(color.green_without, color = "white", background = "#00AA00") %>% row_spec(color.red_without, color = "white", background = "#AA0000") %>% as.character() # Convert it to character to embed HTML within UI explanation <- "

ANCOVA Analysis

The ANCOVA (Analysis of Covariance) assesses whether population means of a dependent variable (response variable) are equal across levels of a categorical independent variable (factor), while controlling for other continuous variables (covariates).

Interaction

The interaction effect in ANCOVA checks if the relationship between covariate and response variable differs across levels of the factor. For a proper ANCOVA, you must meet the assumption of homogeneity of slopes. This is tested using the first analysis, ANCOVA with interaction. If the p value for the interaction (the line with covariate:factor) is non-significant, your data meets the assumption. You can then use the numbers from the ANCOVA without interaction section as your true ANCOVA results.

ANCOVA with interaction:

%s

ANCOVA without interaction:

%s " HTML( sprintf( explanation, ancova_summary_with_int, ancova_summary_without_int ) ) }) ancova_model1 = reactive({ df = data2() validate( need(input$yval != '', 'Please select a y variable'), need(input$factor != '', 'Please select a grouping variable'), need(input$covariate != '', 'Please select a covariate') ) df[[input$yval]] = as.numeric(df[[input$yval]]) df[[input$covariate]] = as.numeric(df[[input$covariate]]) df[[input$factor]] = as.factor(df[[input$factor]]) if (any(is.na(df[[input$yval]])) | any(is.na(df[[input$covariate]]))) { stop( 'The y variable or covariate contains non-numeric values that could not be converted.' ) } aov.i = aov(as.formula( paste( input$yval, '~', input$covariate, '+', input$factor, '+', input$covariate, ':', input$factor ) ), data = df) aov.wo = aov(as.formula(paste( input$yval, '~', input$covariate, '+', input$factor )), data = df) return(list( anc_int = aov.i, anc_no_int = aov.wo )) }) output$posthoc_one_factor <- renderUI({ model <- ancova_model1()[['anc_no_int']] if (is.null(model)) { return( HTML( "

No model available - please ensure data is uploaded and valid selections are made.

" ) ) } emm_result = emmeans(model, specs = input$factor, options = contrasts) pairwise_comparisons <- contrast(emm_result, method = "pairwise", adjust = "holm") %>% as.data.frame() pval <- input$pval # color.green_with <- which(ancova_with_int[, "Pr(>F)"] < pval) # color.red_with <- which(ancova_with_int[, "Pr(>F)"] >= pval) color.green_without <- which(pairwise_comparisons[, "p.value"] < pval) color.red_without <- which(pairwise_comparisons[, "p.value"] >= pval) pairwise_comparisons %>% kbl(format = 'html', escape = F) %>% kable_styling('striped', full_width = F) %>% row_spec(color.green_without, color = "white", background = "#00AA00") %>% row_spec(color.red_without, color = "white", background = "#AA0000") %>% as.character() %>% HTML() }) ########################################################### # # # ########################################################### # Data handling for two factors analysis data1_2way = reactive({ validate(need(input$file2, 'Please upload a CSV file')) inFile = input$file2 if (is.null(inFile)) return(NULL) df = read.csv(inFile$datapath, na.strings = c('', 'NA', '#N/A')) return(df) }) data2way = reactive({ df3 = data1_2way() updateSelectInput(session, 'yval2', choices = colnames(df3)) updateSelectInput(session, 'factor1', choices = colnames(df3)) updateSelectInput(session, 'factor2', choices = colnames(df3)) updateSelectInput(session, 'covariate2', choices = colnames(df3)) return(df3) }) output$normal2 = renderUI({ df = data2way() validate( need(!is.na(df[[input$yval2]]), "Please select a Y variable."), need(is.numeric(df[[input$yval2]]), 'Y variable must be numeric.'), need(!is.factor(df[[input$yval2]]), 'Y Variable cannot be a factor.') ) and_dar = ad.test(df[[input$yval2]])[['p.value']] shapiro = shapiro.test(df[[input$yval2]])[['p.value']] pcutoff = 0.05 ynorm = if (and_dar > pcutoff && shapiro > pcutoff) { 'Your y variable is normally distributed according to both Shapiro-Wilk and Anderson-Darling tests. Proceed with ANCOVA.' } else if (and_dar > pcutoff && shapiro < pcutoff) { '

Your y variable is normally distributed according to the Anderson-Darling test but not the Shapiro-Wilk test. Caution is advised.

' } else if (and_dar < pcutoff && shapiro > pcutoff) { '

Your y variable is normally distributed according to the Shapiro-Wilk test but not the Anderson-Darling test. Caution is advised.

' } else { '

Your y variable is not normally distributed. Serious caution advised.

' } HTML(ynorm) }) # Plot outputs for two factors analysis output$raw_plot2 = renderPlot({ df = data2way() df$cat_factor = paste0(df[[input$factor1]], '\n', df[[input$factor2]]) scatterplot = ggplot( data = df, aes_string( x = input$covariate2, y = input$yval2, color = 'cat_factor', shape = 'cat_factor' ) ) + geom_point() + stat_smooth(method = 'lm') + custom_gg + guides(color = guide_legend(ncol = 1), shape = guide_legend(ncol = 1)) + labs( title = 'Covariate vs. Y Variable', fill = 'Group', color = 'Group', shape = 'Group' ) + theme(legend.position = 'right') groupedplot = ggplot(data = df, aes_string( x = 'cat_factor', y = input$yval2, fill = 'cat_factor' )) + geom_boxplot(colour = 'black') + geom_point(position = position_jitterdodge(jitter.width = 0.2, dodge.width = 0.75)) + custom_gg list(plot.title = element_text(size = 20))) + plot_layout(guides = 'collect') }) output$modelchecks2_int = renderPlot({ model = ancova_model2() model = model[['anc_int']] if (is.null(model)) { return("No model available - please ensure data is uploaded and valid selections are made.") } checks = mod_check(model = model, color = 'cat_factor') checks }) output$modelchecks2_no_int = mod_check(model = model, color = 'cat_factor') checks }) # ANCOVA Explanation for Two Factors Analysis output$ancovaExplanation2 = renderUI({ model = ancova_model2() if (is.null(model)) { return("No model available - please ensure data is uploaded and valid selections are made.") } # Extract ANCOVA summaries ancova_with_int = Anova(model[['anc_int']], type = 'III') ancova_without_int = Anova(model[['anc_no_int']], type = 'III') # Determine rows for coloring based on p-values pval <- input$pval color.green_with <- which(ancova_with_int[, "Pr(>F)"] < pval) color.red_with <- which(ancova_with_int[, "Pr(>F)"] >= pval) color.green_without <- which(ancova_without_int[, "Pr(>F)"] < pval) color.red_without <- which(ancova_without_int[, "Pr(>F)"] >= pval) # Create HTML tables with `kable` ancova_summary_with_int <- ancova_with_int %>% kbl() %>% kable_styling("striped", full_width = F) %>% row_spec(color.green_with, color = "white", background = "#00AA00") %>% row_spec(color.red_with, color = "white", background = "#AA0000") %>% as.character() # Convert it to character to embed HTML within UI ancova_summary_without_int <- ancova_without_int %>% kbl() %>% kable_styling("striped", full_width = F) %>% row_spec(color.green_without, color = "white", background = "#00AA00") %>% row_spec(color.red_without, color = "white", background = "#AA0000") %>% as.character() # Convert it to character to embed HTML within UI explanation = "

ANCOVA Analysis

The ANCOVA (Analysis of Covariance) assesses whether population means of a dependent variable (response variable) are equal across levels of a categorical independent variable (factor), while controlling for other continuous variables (covariates).

Interaction

The interaction effect in ANCOVA checks if the relationship between covariate and response variable differs across levels of the factor. For a proper ANCOVA, you must meet the assumption of homogeneity of slopes. This is tested using the first analysis, ANCOVA with interaction. If the p values for all interactions that include your covariate are non-significant, your data meets the assumption. You can then use the numbers from the ANCOVA without interaction section as your true ANCOVA results.

ANCOVA with interaction:

%s

ANCOVA without interaction:

%s " HTML( sprintf( explanation, ancova_summary_with_int, ancova_summary_without_int ) ) }) ancova_model2 = reactive({ df = data2way() validate( need(input$yval2 != '', 'Please select a y variable'), need(input$factor1 != '', 'Please select grouping variable 1'), need(input$factor2 != '', 'Please select grouping variable 2'), need(input$covariate2 != '', 'Please select a covariate') ) df[[input$yval2]] = as.numeric(df[[input$yval2]]) df[[input$covariate2]] = as.numeric(df[[input$covariate2]]) df[[input$factor1]] = as.factor(df[[input$factor1]]) df[[input$factor2]] = as.factor(df[[input$factor2]]) if (any(is.na(df[[input$yval2]])) | any(is.na(df[[input$covariate2]]))) { stop( 'The y variable or covariate contains non-numeric values that could not be converted.' ) } aov.i = aov(as.formula( paste( input$yval2, '~', input$covariate2, '*', input$factor1, '*', input$factor2 ) ), data = df) aov.i$model$cat_factor = paste0(aov.i$model[[input$factor1]], '\n', aov.i$model[[input$factor2]]) aov.wo = aov(as.formula( paste( input$yval2, '~', input$covariate2, '+', input$factor1 , '+', input$factor2 ) ), data = df) aov.wo$model$cat_factor = paste0(aov.wo$model[[input$factor1]], '\n', aov.wo$model[[input$factor2]]) return(list( anc_int = aov.i, anc_no_int = aov.wo )) }) output$posthoc_two_factor <- renderUI({ model <- ancova_model2() if (is.null(model)) { return( HTML( "

No model available - please ensure data is uploaded and valid selections are made.

" ) ) } # Determine which comparisons to perform based on user selection comparison_factors <- switch( input$comparison_factor, "Factor 1" = input$factor1, "Factor 2" = input$factor2, "All Pairwise" = 'both' ) # Perform the post-hoc analysis based on the chosen comparison factor if (comparison_factors == 'both') { emm_result <- emmeans(model[['anc_no_int']], specs = c(input$factor1, input$factor2), options = contrasts) pairwise_comparisons = contrast(emm_result, method = 'pairwise', adjust = 'tukey') %>% as.data.frame() } else { # Pairwise comparisons for one factor emm_result <- emmeans(model[['anc_no_int']], specs = comparison_factors, options = contrasts) pairwise_comparisons = contrast(emm_result, method = 'pairwise', adjust = 'holm') %>% as.data.frame() } pval <- input$pval # color.green_with <- which(ancova_with_int[, "Pr(>F)"] < pval) # color.red_with <- which(ancova_with_int[, "Pr(>F)"] >= pval) color.green_without <- which(pairwise_comparisons[, "p.value"] < pval) color.red_without <- which(pairwise_comparisons[, "p.value"] >= pval) pairwise_comparisons %>% kbl(format = 'html', escape = F) %>% kable_styling('striped', full_width = F) %>% row_spec(color.green_without, color = "white", background = "#00AA00") %>% row_spec(color.red_without, color = "white", background = "#AA0000") %>% as.character() %>% HTML() }) } shinyApp(ui = ui, server = server)

<script>const sectionChanged = new CustomEvent("quarto-sectionChanged", {
  detail: {},
  bubbles: true,
  cancelable: false,
  composed: false,
});

const layoutMarginEls = () => {
  // Find any conflicting margin elements and add margins to the
  // top to prevent overlap
  const marginChildren = window.document.querySelectorAll(
    ".column-margin.column-container > *, .margin-caption, .aside"
  );

  let lastBottom = 0;
  for (const marginChild of marginChildren) {
    if (marginChild.offsetParent !== null) {
      // clear the top margin so we recompute it
      marginChild.style.marginTop = null;
      const top = marginChild.getBoundingClientRect().top + window.scrollY;
      if (top < lastBottom) {
        const marginChildStyle = window.getComputedStyle(marginChild);
        const marginBottom = parseFloat(marginChildStyle["marginBottom"]);
        const margin = lastBottom - top + marginBottom;
        marginChild.style.marginTop = `${margin}px`;
      }
      const styles = window.getComputedStyle(marginChild);
      const marginTop = parseFloat(styles["marginTop"]);
      lastBottom = top + marginChild.getBoundingClientRect().height + marginTop;
    }
  }
};

window.document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", function (_event) {
  // Recompute the position of margin elements anytime the body size changes
  if (window.ResizeObserver) {
    const resizeObserver = new window.ResizeObserver(
      throttle(() => {
        layoutMarginEls();
        if (
          window.document.body.getBoundingClientRect().width < 990 &&
          isReaderMode()
        ) {
          quartoToggleReader();
        }
      }, 50)
    );
    resizeObserver.observe(window.document.body);
  }

  const tocEl = window.document.querySelector('nav.toc-active[role="doc-toc"]');
  const sidebarEl = window.document.getElementById("quarto-sidebar");
  const leftTocEl = window.document.getElementById("quarto-sidebar-toc-left");
  const marginSidebarEl = window.document.getElementById(
    "quarto-margin-sidebar"
  );
  // function to determine whether the element has a previous sibling that is active
  const prevSiblingIsActiveLink = (el) => {
    const sibling = el.previousElementSibling;
    if (sibling && sibling.tagName === "A") {
      return sibling.classList.contains("active");
    } else {
      return false;
    }
  };

  // fire slideEnter for bootstrap tab activations (for htmlwidget resize behavior)
  function fireSlideEnter(e) {
    const event = window.document.createEvent("Event");
    event.initEvent("slideenter", true, true);
    window.document.dispatchEvent(event);
  }
  const tabs = window.document.querySelectorAll('a[data-bs-toggle="tab"]');
  tabs.forEach((tab) => {
    tab.addEventListener("shown.bs.tab", fireSlideEnter);
  });

  // fire slideEnter for tabby tab activations (for htmlwidget resize behavior)
  document.addEventListener("tabby", fireSlideEnter, false);

  // Track scrolling and mark TOC links as active
  // get table of contents and sidebar (bail if we don't have at least one)
  const tocLinks = tocEl
    ? [...tocEl.querySelectorAll("a[data-scroll-target]")]
    : [];
  const makeActive = (link) => tocLinks[link].classList.add("active");
  const removeActive = (link) => tocLinks[link].classList.remove("active");
  const removeAllActive = () =>
    [...Array(tocLinks.length).keys()].forEach((link) => removeActive(link));

  // activate the anchor for a section associated with this TOC entry
  tocLinks.forEach((link) => {
    link.addEventListener("click", () => {
      if (link.href.indexOf("#") !== -1) {
        const anchor = link.href.split("#")[1];
        const heading = window.document.querySelector(
          `[data-anchor-id="${anchor}"]`
        );
        if (heading) {
          // Add the class
          heading.classList.add("reveal-anchorjs-link");

          // function to show the anchor
          const handleMouseout = () => {
            heading.classList.remove("reveal-anchorjs-link");
            heading.removeEventListener("mouseout", handleMouseout);
          };

          // add a function to clear the anchor when the user mouses out of it
          heading.addEventListener("mouseout", handleMouseout);
        }
      }
    });
  });

  const sections = tocLinks.map((link) => {
    const target = link.getAttribute("data-scroll-target");
    if (target.startsWith("#")) {
      return window.document.getElementById(decodeURI(`${target.slice(1)}`));
    } else {
      return window.document.querySelector(decodeURI(`${target}`));
    }
  });

  const sectionMargin = 200;
  let currentActive = 0;
  // track whether we've initialized state the first time
  let init = false;

  const updateActiveLink = () => {
    // The index from bottom to top (e.g. reversed list)
    let sectionIndex = -1;
    if (
      window.innerHeight + window.pageYOffset >=
      window.document.body.offsetHeight
    ) {
      // This is the no-scroll case where last section should be the active one
      sectionIndex = 0;
    } else {
      // This finds the last section visible on screen that should be made active
      sectionIndex = [...sections].reverse().findIndex((section) => {
        if (section) {
          return window.pageYOffset >= section.offsetTop - sectionMargin;
        } else {
          return false;
        }
      });
    }
    if (sectionIndex > -1) {
      const current = sections.length - sectionIndex - 1;
      if (current !== currentActive) {
        removeAllActive();
        currentActive = current;
        makeActive(current);
        if (init) {
          window.dispatchEvent(sectionChanged);
        }
        init = true;
      }
    }
  };

  const inHiddenRegion = (top, bottom, hiddenRegions) => {
    for (const region of hiddenRegions) {
      if (top <= region.bottom && bottom >= region.top) {
        return true;
      }
    }
    return false;
  };

  const categorySelector = "header.quarto-title-block .quarto-category";
  const activateCategories = (href) => {
    // Find any categories
    // Surround them with a link pointing back to:
    // #category=Authoring
    try {
      const categoryEls = window.document.querySelectorAll(categorySelector);
      for (const categoryEl of categoryEls) {
        const categoryText = categoryEl.textContent;
        if (categoryText) {
          const link = `${href}#category=${encodeURIComponent(categoryText)}`;
          const linkEl = window.document.createElement("a");
          linkEl.setAttribute("href", link);
          for (const child of categoryEl.childNodes) {
            linkEl.append(child);
          }
          categoryEl.appendChild(linkEl);
        }
      }
    } catch {
      // Ignore errors
    }
  };
  function hasTitleCategories() {
    return window.document.querySelector(categorySelector) !== null;
  }

  function offsetRelativeUrl(url) {
    const offset = getMeta("quarto:offset");
    return offset ? offset + url : url;
  }

  function offsetAbsoluteUrl(url) {
    const offset = getMeta("quarto:offset");
    const baseUrl = new URL(offset, window.location);

    const projRelativeUrl = url.replace(baseUrl, "");
    if (projRelativeUrl.startsWith("/")) {
      return projRelativeUrl;
    } else {
      return "/" + projRelativeUrl;
    }
  }

  // read a meta tag value
  function getMeta(metaName) {
    const metas = window.document.getElementsByTagName("meta");
    for (let i = 0; i < metas.length; i++) {
      if (metas[i].getAttribute("name") === metaName) {
        return metas[i].getAttribute("content");
      }
    }
    return "";
  }

  async function findAndActivateCategories() {
    const currentPagePath = offsetAbsoluteUrl(window.location.href);
    const response = await fetch(offsetRelativeUrl("listings.json"));
    if (response.status == 200) {
      return response.json().then(function (listingPaths) {
        const listingHrefs = [];
        for (const listingPath of listingPaths) {
          const pathWithoutLeadingSlash = listingPath.listing.substring(1);

<section id="why-use-ancova-to-analyze-mouse-metabolic-data" class="level1">
<h1>Why use ANCOVA to analyze mouse metabolic data?</h1>
<section id="basic-points" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="basic-points">Basic Points</h2>
<ul>
<li><p>ANCOVA should be used to correct for mass differences when analyzing energy expenditure <span class="citation" data-cites="mullerRevisitingEnergyExpenditure2021a">(<a href="#ref-mullerRevisitingEnergyExpenditure2021a" role="doc-biblioref">Müller, Klingenspor, and Tschöp 2021</a>)</span>.</p></li>
<li><p>Choose the appropriate covariate when analyzing energy expenditure, if mice differ greatly in lean mass, choose lean mass but if mice differ greatly in fat mass, total body weight is probably a better choice <span class="citation" data-cites="virtueWhatMostAppropriate2021">(<a href="#ref-virtueWhatMostAppropriate2021" role="doc-biblioref">Virtue, Lelliott, and Vidal-Puig 2021</a>)</span>.</p></li>
<li><p>ANCOVA should be used to analyze mouse food intake if the groups differ by starting body weight <span class="citation" data-cites="allardFoodIntakeBody2022a">(<a href="#ref-allardFoodIntakeBody2022a" role="doc-biblioref">Allard et al. 2022</a>)</span>.</p></li>
</ul>
</section>
<section id="detailed-analysisdiscussion" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="detailed-analysisdiscussion">Detailed Analysis/Discussion</h2>
<ul>
<li><p>Speakman <em>et al.</em> lay out the ANCOVA steps in <span class="citation" data-cites="speakman39StepsAlgorithm2013">(<a href="#ref-speakman39StepsAlgorithm2013" role="doc-biblioref">Speakman, Fletcher, and Vaanholt 2013</a>)</span>.</p></li>
<li><p>Further information on energy metabolism analysis by Tschöp <em>et al.</em> <span class="citation" data-cites="tschopGuideAnalysisMouse2011">(<a href="#ref-tschopGuideAnalysisMouse2011" role="doc-biblioref">Tschop et al. 2011</a>)</span>.</p></li>
<li><p><span class="citation" data-cites="fernandez-verdejoProgressChallengesAnalyzing2019a">(<a href="#ref-fernandez-verdejoProgressChallengesAnalyzing2019a" role="doc-biblioref">Fernández-Verdejo et al. 2019</a>)</span>.</p></li>
</ul>

</section>
</section>

    var localhostRegex = new RegExp(/^(?:http|https):\/\/localhost\:?[0-9]*\//);

  const noterefs = window.document.querySelectorAll('a[role="doc-noteref"]');

      }
    }, function(instance) {
    });
  }
      let selectedAnnoteEl;
      const selectorForAnnotation = ( cell, annotation) => {
        let cellAttr = 'data-code-cell="' + cell + '"';
        let lineAttr = 'data-code-annotation="' +  annotation + '"';
        const selector = 'span[' + cellAttr + '][' + lineAttr + ']';
        return selector;
      }
      const selectCodeLines = (annoteEl) => {
        const doc = window.document;
        const targetCell = annoteEl.getAttribute("data-target-cell");
        const targetAnnotation = annoteEl.getAttribute("data-target-annotation");
        const annoteSpan = window.document.querySelector(selectorForAnnotation(targetCell, targetAnnotation));
        const lines = annoteSpan.getAttribute("data-code-lines").split(",");
        const lineIds = lines.map((line) => {
          return targetCell + "-" + line;
        })
        let top = null;
        let height = null;
        let parent = null;
        if (lineIds.length > 0) {
            //compute the position of the single el (top and bottom and make a div)
            const el = window.document.getElementById(lineIds[0]);
            top = el.offsetTop;
            height = el.offsetHeight;
            parent = el.parentElement.parentElement;
          if (lineIds.length > 1) {
            const lastEl = window.document.getElementById(lineIds[lineIds.length - 1]);
            const bottom = lastEl.offsetTop + lastEl.offsetHeight;
            height = bottom - top;
          }
          if (top !== null && height !== null && parent !== null) {
            // cook up a div (if necessary) and position it 
            let div = window.document.getElementById("code-annotation-line-highlight");
            if (div === null) {
              div = window.document.createElement("div");
              div.setAttribute("id", "code-annotation-line-highlight");
              div.style.position = 'absolute';
              parent.appendChild(div);
            }
            div.style.top = top - 2 + "px";
            div.style.height = height + 4 + "px";
            div.style.left = 0;
            let gutterDiv = window.document.getElementById("code-annotation-line-highlight-gutter");
            if (gutterDiv === null) {
              gutterDiv = window.document.createElement("div");
              gutterDiv.setAttribute("id", "code-annotation-line-highlight-gutter");
              gutterDiv.style.position = 'absolute';
              const codeCell = window.document.getElementById(targetCell);
              const gutter = codeCell.querySelector('.code-annotation-gutter');
              gutter.appendChild(gutterDiv);
            }
            gutterDiv.style.top = top - 2 + "px";
            gutterDiv.style.height = height + 4 + "px";
          }
          selectedAnnoteEl = annoteEl;
        }
      };
      const unselectCodeLines = () => {
        const elementsIds = ["code-annotation-line-highlight", "code-annotation-line-highlight-gutter"];
        elementsIds.forEach((elId) => {
          const div = window.document.getElementById(elId);
          if (div) {
            div.remove();
          }
        });
        selectedAnnoteEl = undefined;
      };
        // Handle positioning of the toggle
    window.addEventListener(
      "resize",
      throttle(() => {
        elRect = undefined;
        if (selectedAnnoteEl) {
          selectCodeLines(selectedAnnoteEl);
        }
      }, 10)
    );
    function throttle(fn, ms) {
    let throttle = false;
    let timer;
      return (...args) => {
        if(!throttle) { // first call gets through
            fn.apply(this, args);
            throttle = true;
        } else { // all the others get throttled
            if(timer) clearTimeout(timer); // cancel #2
            timer = setTimeout(() => {
              fn.apply(this, args);
              timer = throttle = false;
            }, ms);
        }
      };
    }
      // Attach click handler to the DT
      const annoteDls = window.document.querySelectorAll('dt[data-target-cell]');
      for (const annoteDlNode of annoteDls) {
        annoteDlNode.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
          const clickedEl = event.target;
          if (clickedEl !== selectedAnnoteEl) {
            unselectCodeLines();
            const activeEl = window.document.querySelector('dt[data-target-cell].code-annotation-active');
            if (activeEl) {
              activeEl.classList.remove('code-annotation-active');
            }
            selectCodeLines(clickedEl);
            clickedEl.classList.add('code-annotation-active');
          } else {
            // Unselect the line
            unselectCodeLines();
            clickedEl.classList.remove('code-annotation-active');
          }
        });
      }
  const findCites = (el) => {
    const parentEl = el.parentElement;
    if (parentEl) {
      const cites = parentEl.dataset.cites;
      if (cites) {
        return {
          el,
          cites: cites.split(' ')
        };
      } else {
        return findCites(el.parentElement)
      }
    } else {
      return undefined;
    }
  };
  var bibliorefs = window.document.querySelectorAll('a[role="doc-biblioref"]');
  for (var i=0; i<bibliorefs.length; i++) {
    const ref = bibliorefs[i];
    const citeInfo = findCites(ref);
    if (citeInfo) {
      tippyHover(citeInfo.el, function() {
        var popup = window.document.createElement('div');
        citeInfo.cites.forEach(function(cite) {
          var citeDiv = window.document.createElement('div');
          citeDiv.classList.add('hanging-indent');
          citeDiv.classList.add('csl-entry');
          var biblioDiv = window.document.getElementById('ref-' + cite);
          if (biblioDiv) {
            citeDiv.innerHTML = biblioDiv.innerHTML;
          }
          popup.appendChild(citeDiv);
        });
        return popup.innerHTML;
      });
    }
  }
});
</script>
</div> <!-- /content -->
